Monks are unarmed melee fighters trained through the Interior Forms, a systematic discipline of body and mind integration.
The tradition originates from pre-city mountain monasteries where high-altitude conditions favored breath efficiency over raw power.
The Interior Forms have three layers: Outer Forms (stance, footwork), Inner Forms (breath control, energy circulation), and Deepest Forms (full integration).
Combat role is sustained melee fighter whose effectiveness increases as a fight extends.
Key abilities center on chi manipulation, breath control, postural stability, and footwork economy.
The Forms were originally developed as meditation. Martial application was discovered as a side effect.
Monasteries formalized combat training only in response to external threats.
Monks contrast with Brawlers: Monks begin from theory, Brawlers begin from practice.
The Martial Artist class synthesizes Monk discipline with Brawler pragmatism.
Sparring in narrow mountain passes shaped the tradition toward economy of movement over aggression.
